  "introduction": "The rapid proliferation of social media platforms over the last two decades has fundamentally altered the landscape of adolescent development, creating a complex digital environment that shapes how young people perceive themselves and interact with the world. As teenagers increasingly spend hours scrolling through feeds, sharing curated images, and connecting with peers globally, the consequences of this digital immersion are becoming increasingly visible. Researchers and educators alike are observing a significant shift in daily routines, where the boundary between online and offline existence blurs, leading to unique challenges that were previously unknown. The sheer volume of data generated by these interactions suggests that the way adolescents consume and produce content is reshaping their fundamental understanding of social norms, self-worth, and community belonging. This transformation is not merely a change in communication style but a profound restructuring of the developmental experience, forcing a reevaluation of how young minds navigate an era defined by constant connectivity and instant feedback loops that can amplify both positive reinforcement and negative comparison.",
